        <sharedstimulus id="assets/85eae80363574605cac71/passage NEW 1.xml">
            <label key="61e09a4fc843ed8413561abf8234004d">
                <text>Polar Bears</text>
            </label>
            <label key="0d6b092a549539715b40e0c6f557f3a0">
                <text>Over recent decades, polar bears have spent more time on land.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="5ef4b71500037a4dde04825705d4a1b1">
                <text>This has led to more interactions between bears and humans. In some cases, these interactions cause serious conflict that may endanger human life or damage property.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="37a16a9dd6e2020b44244fd4b481b648">
                <text>This graph summarises the types of bear and human interactions that result in serious conflicts. The data was collected from villages in the Chukchi Sea area.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="947042829432516b2f3fab964c8ae7e6">
                <text>Bear finds human food or rubbish<br/><strong>31%</strong></text>
            </label>
            <label key="16aa937a8abc4bcbf4538f1d8726d374">
                <text>Safety officers manage bears to protect the community<br/><strong>15%</strong></text>
            </label>
            <label key="cf78c4f70315a09a2711b67aace50f15">
                <text>Bear approaches dog<br/><strong>15%</strong></text>
            </label>
            <label key="6147dffd59a0f05c7ababc276e13e3cd">
                <text>Human activities occur in polar bear territory<br/><strong>9%</strong></text>
            </label>
            <label key="c7f8cc547956bf520a06c0f2f8caf76c">
                <text>Bear attacks human<br/><strong>6%</strong></text>
            </label>
            <label key="bc2c2315b03085fef037cc7d2679a13a">
                <text>Bear protects cubs<br/><strong>6%</strong></text>
            </label>
            <label key="7d110d7ef023a7d60e13a946153ad941">
                <text>Bear is aggresive to human<br/><strong>4%</strong></text>
            </label>
            <label key="e27046ff3f4297e6c88c729e74c93005">
                <text>Human provikes bear<br/><strong>4%</strong></text>
            </label>
            <label key="be0787f565725fa6c20ceeb0979b8601">
                <text>Human approaches bear out of curiosity<br/><strong>4%</strong></text>
            </label>
            <label key="2c75ca50d50ce17dbd056aac9d479cdf">
                <text>Bear defends food (animal carcass)<br/><strong>2%</strong></text>
            </label>
            <label key="9c9731cd3da4b948fec51f49b9d3d200">
                <text>Bear travels through human area<br/><strong>2%</strong></text>
            </label>
            <label key="977bd069e2acb0c884b0266488691aca">
                <text>Human shoots and wounds bear<br/><strong>2%</strong></text>
            </label>
        </sharedstimulus>
    </sharedstimuli>
    <items>
        <item id="i63574781e3ad6194519c11d475a0d8166a">
            <label key="f4aff5a19a5c67248d77737ceef0a981">
                <text>At a community meeting, a villager from the Chukchi Sea area said that if you do not approach polar bears, they will not cause you harm.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="46058032bcf480a27673dd7bb3f0e32d">
                <text>Does the data in the graph support this claim?</text>
            </label>
            <label key="93cba07454f06a4a960172bbd6e2a435">
                <text>Yes</text>
            </label>
            <label key="bafd7322c6e97d25b6299b5d6fe8920b">
                <text>No</text>
            </label>
            <label key="4fd72ad9efa6be34b8ac1f513e76dfb5">
                <text>Explain your answer.</text>
            </label>
        </item>
        <item id="i635747b475dad2694a89a3a127a0ac698">
            <label key="0ca94815c73c75d4c3c553ec1c87fcdc">
                <text>Based on the data in the graph, explain one action that villagers could take that would address the largest cause of serious conflict between bears and humans.</text>
            </label>
        </item>
    </items>
